Read the wording of each input carefully:
- a **standard deviation** is *already* $u$ (no divisor);
- a **variance** needs a square root, $u=\sqrt V$;
- an **expanded uncertainty** is divided by its coverage factor, $u=U/k$;
- a **maximum spread / range / tolerance / resolution** is a half-width and takes a distribution divisor ($\sqrt3$, $\sqrt2$ or $\sqrt6$).
Confusing these four is the single most common way to lose marks.

By convention assign to a Type B (variability-interval) contribution:
- **$\nu=100$** when the information is *extremely consolidated*;
- **$\nu=30$** when *consolidated*;
- **$\nu=15$** when it is *to be checked*.
(GUM nominally suggests $\infty$; ~100 is a common working value.) A higher $\nu$ means a more trusted contribution.
